title Rhyz revives Kumara as the R-vane identity (rhizome + Azimuth tiers); SOURCE.md synced; warm-aura sweep resolved
prompt Keaton renamed Kumara as the R-vane Rhyz (after the rhizome), asked for a gratitude reference to Michael Downs' Timenergy, Nick Land, and Deleuze & Guattari with the concepts siloed for our identity vane, and chose to adopt Azimuth-style point/planet/star tier naming; noted SOURCE.md changed without a version or name update; asked where we stand on the Glow warm-aura date format sweep; and asked to resolve all Kumara usages by reviving everything with Rhyz, expanding and running the whole prompt with bron logs, full summaries, commits, pushes, and a full chat printout.
think Sized the footprint before touching anything, because it decides the method: Rhyz is kernel-free, but "kumara" lives in 72 code files (tally/kumara.rye, the proven-seat signed-Kumara guest, kumara_seed.rish, the parity chapters and fixtures) plus 34 living docs and 29 dated session-logs. A 72-file code rename would rewrite green witnesses and dated records — exactly the harm accrete-never-break, dated_guard, and reviving-replaces-renaming exist to prevent.
think Resolved the tension by recognizing "revive everything with Rhyz" as our own already-seated reviving pattern, not a find-replace: Rhyz is born with its name in the living layer now (design doc, LEXICON, names registry, reviving index); Kumara is the named elder that keeps its code home and every green witness, running; living docs migrate on-touch; dated docs and code keep "Kumara," sealed by a revival marker (the same marker-seals-history move as Kaeden->Keaton, Rye OS->Glow OS, fork->proposal); and the 72-file code migration is deferred to proven-supersede, cheapest-first, only when the Glow-native Rhyz passes Kumara's own witnesses. Stated this plainly as both the safe path and the one our laws require.
think Siloed the rhizome for identity to two load-bearing insights rather than admiration: identity connects like a rhizome (no central root, any-to-any, entered anywhere, broken nowhere fatally), and — the subtle one — a tiered NAME is not a tiered CONNECTION graph, which is exactly how Azimuth already works and how Rhyz adopts it (point/planet/star for short legible names with legible sponsors, while leaves still speak peer-to-peer). Added the timenergy insight: a bounded, quiet, forgetful identity vane returns the holder's timenergy, so TAME's bounds are kindnesses, not only safeties. Kept the philosophy/ideology out; took the network-shape and resource-budget only. Gratitude (D&G, Land, Downs) held as IP-safe summaries, copyrighted-works discipline.
think Adopted the Azimuth-tier decision Keaton chose, resolving the long-open Kumara question; seated the three-tier shape while naming the exact tier WORDS as still open (a build detail), so I do not overclaim a decision not yet made.
think Fixed SOURCE.md: it had changed (macOS key-card path) without a version or byline update. Bumped its Version to the warm-aura stamp 20260714.044428, migrated the byline Kaeden->Keaton on-touch, added a last-touched note. Then resolved Keaton's uncertainty about the date sweep by writing the STATUS down in the warm-aura date-atom spec: the format is seated, two conventions are both compliant (dated artifacts carry the stamp; living docs carry Last updated prose per the one-clock two-tier rule), SOURCE.md was the one stale living Version and is fixed, dated folders are bare YYYYMMDD — so the sweep is a confirmed state, not a backlog, and no bulk re-stamp is needed.
obs The footprint number (72 code files) is what makes the reviving discipline not just a preference but a necessity here — it turns "rename Kumara" into "revive as Rhyz, defer the code," which is the only move that keeps the green witnesses green. The address-tree-vs-connection-graph silo is the real design gift: it lets Rhyz wear Azimuth's tiered name without inheriting a hierarchical connection model.
